<div id="review_865565353" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/865565353" />
    <a title="Idea Smith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3530445-idea-smith"><img alt="Idea Smith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381707158p2/3530445.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/865565353?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Idea Smith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Idea Smith" href="/user/show/3530445-idea-smith">Idea Smith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780440108269" href="/book/show/53502.The_Bridge_Across_Forever">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer865565353" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2680166686956531294">I read this book as a teenager among a flurry of other Bach books. While the others pontificated and shared ideas that I&apos;m still pondering, this one brought the concept of love in a modern world, outside of fairytales. I read this again, as an adult, all these years later. And I realise what a good thing it was to have read a love story of this sort when I was young. It&apos;s honest, brutal at times. It doesn&apos;t paint love as a &apos;happily ever after&apos; concept. Bach and Leslie have their fair share of pr</span>
  <span id="freeText2680166686956531294" style="display:none">I read this book as a teenager among a flurry of other Bach books. While the others pontificated and shared ideas that I'm still pondering, this one brought the concept of love in a modern world, outside of fairytales. I read this again, as an adult, all these years later. And I realise what a good thing it was to have read a love story of this sort when I was young. It's honest, brutal at times. It doesn't paint love as a 'happily ever after' concept. Bach and Leslie have their fair share of problems, with include commitment phobia, different ideals and personality clashes. They also battle the money monster as Bach receives a windfall, then blunders through it into a financial crisis. And at the end, both their notions of love and soul mates are greatly changed. Each lets go of something that they thought they needed in a perfect soulmate, each gets something unexpected in return.<br /><br />A sweet love story and much more realistic one for our times than most ChickLit &amp; Mills &amp; Boons.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2680166686956531294" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review865565353">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
